column8: Department of Defense (DoD) operations are supported by a vast global network of computers, sensors, and equipment that is continually at risk of being breached by adversaries.  Despite heavy investments in security and cyber defense, the sheer ubiquity and interconnectedness of DoD equipment leave open the possibility of intrusion through a myriad of means including advanced persistent threats (APTs).  Such threats take many forms, such as Trojans, back-doors in embedded systems, worms, spear-phishing, and viruses, all of which could prove detrimental to the war-fighter if not discovered. Recent examples of such advanced attacks include Stuxnet and Flame.   Detecting such threats requires novel techniques that are not signature based, since such attacks (or, at the very least, the most dangerous ones) are often customized for a particular target, perhaps based upon substantial intelligence gathering.Accordingly, we intend to use the SKAION 2009 DARPA Dataset to test our novel anomaly detection algorithms.  This data set will provide both background "signal" into which we can inject our own anomalous measurements, as well as providing a data set with its own inherent anomalies.  Our main computational tools will be advanced ideas from multi-sensor fusion, compressed sensing, and dependency analysis.This work is currently being funded by the Office of the Secretary of Defense under contract #W911QX-13-C-0015.

column8: Firewalls are the primary security devices in cyber defense. Yet, the security of firewalls depends on the quality of protection obtained by the firewall policy hardening.The lack of metrics and attack incident data make measuring the security of firewall policies a challenging task. This requires defining a set of objective metrics to measure and to compare quality of protection of firewall policies objectively.This research project intends to propose a new set of quantitative metrics that can be used to measure and to compare the security level of firewall policies in an enterprise network. The presented metrics should be proven to be (1) valid as compared with the ground truth, and (2) practically useful as each one implies actionable security hardening. Ã¢Â€ÂœDShield dataset Ã¢Â€Âœ will be used to show that the implementation and usability of these metrics are attainable and affordable.

column8: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks. Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node. This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies. This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.

column8: Our dependence on the Internet has rapidly grown much stronger than ourcomprehension of its underlying structure, global dynamics, operationalthreats, and overall network health. Wide-scale Internet service disruptionsand even politically motivated interference with Internet access in orderto hinder anti-government organization are not new.We have developed a methodology, using dark space data from the UCSD NetworkTelescope, that can identify which networks are affected by an outage, andwhich techniques are used to effect a deliberate disruption. We have alsodeveloped metrics to quantitatively gauge the geographic and topologicalextent of the impact of geophysical disasters on Internet infrastructure, andtechniques to investigate the chronological dynamics of the outage andrestoration.The USC Lander address history and hitlist datasets will provide referenceinformation on normally reachable hosts/networks for the study and targetedanalysis of these large-scale Internet outages.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute
column19: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

Wide-scale Internet service disruptionsand even politically motivated interference with Internet access in orderto hinder anti-government organization are not new.We have developed a methodology, using dark space data from the UCSD NetworkTelescope, that can identify which networks are affected by an outage, andwhich techniques are used to effect a deliberate disruption. We have alsodeveloped metrics to quantitatively gauge the geographic and topologicalextent of the impact of geophysical disasters on Internet infrastructure, andtechniques to investigate the chronological dynamics of the outage andrestoration.The USC Lander address history and hitlist datasets will provide referenceinformation on normally reachable hosts/networks for the study and targetedanalysis of these large-scale Internet outages.

Wide-scale Internet service disruptionsand even politically motivated interference with Internet access in orderto hinder anti-government organization are not new.We have developed a methodology, using dark space data from the UCSD NetworkTelescope, that can identify which networks are affected by an outage, andwhich techniques are used to effect a deliberate disruption. We have alsodeveloped metrics to quantitatively gauge the geographic and topologicalextent of the impact of geophysical disasters on Internet infrastructure, andtechniques to investigate the chronological dynamics of the outage andrestoration.The USC Lander address history and hitlist datasets will provide referenceinformation on normally reachable hosts/networks for the study and targetedanalysis of these large-scale Internet outages.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute
column19: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

column8: For purposes of our research, we propose to use this data to study abnormalities in network activity. An abnormality i network activity/traffic flow is determined by an unusual shift or increase from the base probability between two given nodes. The objective of this study is to understand and define the normal occurrence of activity on a network using a scanning approach, in order to be able to detect any anomalies or groups of anomalies (an anomalous window) in the traffic flow and how it relates to particular topology of nodes in the network. The contributions of this study are directed towards providing new insights on the issue of cyber security, particularly from a data mining perspective.

The contributions of this study are directed towards providing new insights on the issue of cyber security, particularly from a data mining perspective.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: The basis of the research is to study the feature of various network flows and use the parametric estimation method and fitting test to find the difference between the flows in their distribution and parameters. We would apply for three datasets: Dos 80-20110715, UniformnAttack Traces Generated20070821-20041202 and UniformAttack traces-20070115.DoS 80-20110715 is used to study DoS attack with background traffic. UniformnAttack Traces Generated20070821-20041202 and UniformAttack traces-20070115 are used to study the same uniform attack with different background traffic. We will use statistical software such as Matlab to get the statistical characteristics and then more researches will be done. We will be appreciated if our request are approved.

column8: This work is part of CAIDA's SaTC project ("Detection and analysis of large-scale Internet infrastructure outages") funded by NSF.  All work will be conducted at CAIDA, UC San Diego.          http://www.caida.org/funding/satc/This project will result in an experimental operational deployment to validate and extend an empirically-grounded methodology for detection and analysis of large-scale Internet outages. In addition to improving our understanding of how measurements yield insights into network behavior, and strengthening our ability to model large scale complex networks, use of such a system will also illuminate infrastructure vulnerabilities that derive from architectural, topological, or economic constraints, suggesting how to mitigate or eliminate these weaknesses in future Internet architecture and measurement research. A deployed platform will be able to detect and monitor connectivity disruption and censorship events on a planetary scale thus enabling situational awareness of the nature and causes of network outages to national decision-makers who must determine the type and extent of proper response.We need a set of known responding destinations so that we can regularly probe them to determine outages caused by Hurricane Sandy and other causes.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: We are currently exploring the implications of deploying RPKI in the global Internet.  RPKI is a public key infrastructure for internet routing, as well an authenticated mapping from AS to IP prefixes.  We will use this dataset to map ASes to organizations, so we can understand the role of different organizations in the power structure of the RPKI.

column8: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks. Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node. This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies. This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.

column8: During the early days of the Information Age routine network security was often as simple as monitoring log files or writing scripts, but with modern advents such as Cluster and Grid computing global network traffic has increased from 0.001 PB/month (1990) to 27,483 PB/month (2011).  Simply put, the volume of data is now unmanageable by human operators or even intrusion detection scripts.  Our research aims to utilize software Intelligent Agents (IA's) and IBM InfoSphere Streams to develop a framework that performs realtime (sub-second) data analytics on network traffic.  The IA's receive inbound network data and use machine-learning algorithms to dynamically assess and counter cyber attacks.  Our organization will use data provided by PREDICT to provide an initial 'training' sandbox environment for the IA's.  This seed data will allow the IA's to gain knowledge about the network topology, packet structures, methods of attack, and learn what a 'normal' (no attacks occurring) stream of traffic should look like.  After the initial training of the IA's a different data set will be used to test the learning capabilities and response actions of the IA's, allowing our organization to perform a rigorous analysis on the performance of our framework.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: Our research focuses on optimizing Intrusion Detection System rulesets. Although rule based IDSes are widely deployed, not all rules are appropriate for all installations. A particular IDS deployment observes distinct traffic and threats, and has unique resource limitations. Using inappropriate rules can lead to an increased false positive rate, by matching traffic that is not malicious at a particular deployment, or a decreased detection rate, by wasting resources that could be used to match rules more appropriate for a particular deployment. We will use this data to build and evaluate a collaborative IDS ruleset optimization system, which predicts which rules are appropriate for a particular IDS deployment based on past performance and statistics at other, correlated, IDS deployments.
column14: Merit Network, Inc.

column8: In this research project, we'll evaluate various IP reputation, DNSBL and DNSWL (email Spam black- and whitelists based on DNS), and BGP based feeds for their relevancy, using the PREDICT data sets. Scope of this research is Network IPS (Intrustion Prevention Systems) and enhancing them with IP reputation technology. We've selected the two data sets, which both have real non-anonymized IP address records, and are updated on the regular basis. We'll validate these real IP addresses against various reputation feeds and estimate False Positive, False Negative rates as well as overall hit and match rate.

column8: We are requesting the Data for the project PEARL (described below). Please note that the people with access to the data are all US Citizens)PEARL Ã¢Â€Â“ Preempt Evolve Act Review Learn (PEARL) PEARL incorporates a trust management framework and learning system with the ultimate goals of identifying those entities in the environment that are not trustworthy, and responding to potential threats in an automated, real-time fashion. Changes in trust levels over time, we suggest, provide an indication of the behavior of a node. The changes are used by PEARL to make a decision as to how to react. PEARL will be given knowledge of the trust relationships in the environment, will assign trust values to those relationships (per node), and will maintain a history of past trust values. The system will then use changes in trust values over time to identify patterns of behavior and decide how to react.

column8: We are requesting the Data for the project PEARL (described below). Please note that the people with access to the data are all US Citizens)PEARL Ã¢Â€Â“ Preempt Evolve Act Review Learn (PEARL) PEARL incorporates a trust management framework and learning system with the ultimate goals of identifying those entities in the environment that are not trustworthy, and responding to potential threats in an automated, real-time fashion. Changes in trust levels over time, we suggest, provide an indication of the behavior of a node. The changes are used by PEARL to make a decision as to how to react. PEARL will be given knowledge of the trust relationships in the environment, will assign trust values to those relationships (per node), and will maintain a history of past trust values. The system will then use changes in trust values over time to identify patterns of behavior and decide how to react.

column8: In this work we are developing a mathematical and computational framework for detecting and classifying weak, distributed patterns in sensor networks.  Our algorithms center on the innovative use of space-time inference on graphs, robust matrix completion and second order analysis to collect data from across a network, and reveal the presence of patterns that are not discernible at the level of an individual node.   This data will be used to test new techniques in unsupervised learning that detecting anomalies in network derived time series as well as probe network topologies.  This work is currently being funded by the Air Force Office of Scientific under contract #FA9550-10-C-0090.
column14: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

column8: Investigate the possibility of performing streaming analytics on pcap and flow data as part of work being proposed under NSA BAA 002-12.  In addition, the data may be used for evaluating other analytical approaches being incorporated into new analytical tools being developed by RedJack.The analytics to be performed will include scan detection, host profiling, and anomalous network volume behaviors at the host, protocol, and port levels.  A continuous dataset is a prerequisite for this activity.  The techniques developed will ultimately be adapted to real time processing of both flow and packet streams. Since the catalog does not indicate the time periods covered by most of the requested data sets, they are being requested in their entirety.  It is likely that the entire sets will not be needed, but this cannot be determined without additional information.  At this time we believe that samples of at least a few days to a few months duration will suffice.

column8: The increasing volume of security alert data arising from the variety of security-enforcement systems connected to the enterprise - has made responding the most crucial events more difficult.  In order to adequately respond to these attacks we propose a triage engine that review and correlates alert issues by intrusion detection systems and prioritizes them for security officers, based on the associated risk.  We would like to evaluate our engine using the Skaion dataset.  In particularly, we would like to validate that our alert triage engine assigns higher risk scores to alerts, as a multi-stage attack progresses to more advanced stages.
column14: SKAION

column8: I am developing sketch based algorithms which estimates distinct elements over sliding window in the traffic data. Such abrupt changes can indicate possible anomalies in the network which plays an important role in network monitoring.  And I need traffic data under attack scenarios to test the efficacy of my algorithms.  This is why I'm asking for the datasets on the list.

column8: For purposes of our research, we propose to use this data to study abnormalities in network activity. An abnormality in network activity/traffic flow is determined by an unusual shift or increase from the base probability between two givennodes. The objective of this study is to understand and define the normal occurrence of activity on a network using ascanning approach, in order to be able to detect any anomalies or groups of anomalies (an anomalous window) in thetraffic flow and how it related to particular topology of nodes in the network. The contributions of this study are directed towards providing new insights on the issue of cyber security, particularly from a data mining perspective.

The contributions of this study are directed towards providing new insights on the issue of cyber security, particularly from a data mining perspective.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: Fraunhofer has developed a real-time, graphical visualization for application and network events. This application is novel in the nature of the graphical representations. while most visual representations are network diagrams or statistical charts, our visualization provides a novel animation of ongoing events as well as a historical view over time. Wecurrently have a research prototype that functions on syslog events, as well as IIS and Apache webserver application events. We would like to request these datasets to test the scalability of our application, to expand our application to pcap, and to have a sizeable dataset with known attacks for experimentation purposes.

column8: We wish to test the hypothesis that a Logistic Regression model can identify adversary behavior in sensor data.  We seek synthetic data for model development and evaluation.  We would also seek to compare the performance of any resulting models to data in the 1999 DARPA data set.
column14: SKAION

column8: Advanced statistical methods appear missing from most discussions of cyber threats and cyber security.  In this project, I intend to analyze Internet traffic over both space and time, specifically with the goal to reliably predict the incidence, frequency, duration and scope of cyber threats and cyber attacks.  Ideally the data will allow me apply advanced statistical methods for analyzing both time series, panel and duration data to cyber traffic data collected from routers in different countries between the years 1998 through 2008.  By mapping, so to speak, the frequency and intensity of Internet traffic within these dimensions and ultimately tying anomalies in the data to predictable events (e.g.cyber attacks), we seeks to enhance the understanding and discussion of how, when, and to what degree security attacks occur (including multiple and various types of disruptions).  The insights gained from this will serve organizations in the public and private sector seeking to thwart attacks and reduce the economic and social costs of such attacks.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: This dataset will be analyzed as part of our research on security analytics. We are interested in analyzing IP packets network traffic to understand how to improve incident detection rate in terms of accuracy and possibly efficiency. We will mine the data and use graphical representation of the data (through oriented graphs) to uncover patterns and anomalies.

column6: William Eberle, TTU, Box 5101, Cookeville, TN, 931-372-3278, weberle@tntech.edu
column8: My research involves the detection of anomalies in data represented as a graph.  Currently, I am working on a grant with the Department of Homeland Security, on the analysis of large graphs consisting of cargo shipments into the U.S.  One issue that I am attempting to address is the detection of anomalies in data that is being streamed (e.g., network data).  Because I need data that contains both normal traffic as well as anomalous traffic (in this case, malicious traffic), this dataset will serve as a good test for my experiments.
column14: SKAION

column8: We are developing algorithms for detecting anomalies in network data represented as a graph. This dataset will be very useful for evaluating our tools, especially since it contains both normal and anomalous traffic, and ground truth. We will use the dataset to evaluation various anomaly detection algorithms and graph representations for these types of attacks.
column14: SKAION

column6: Loai Zomlot, lzomlot@ksu.edu, Kansas State University, 234 Nichols Hall, Manhattan, KS Sathya Chandran, sathya@ksu.edu, Kansas State University, 234 Nichols Hall, Manhattan, KS
column8: We have been conducting intrusion analysis research based on a research prototype tool called SnIPS developed at Kansas State University. We need data with mixed attack and benign traffic with documented ground truth to evaluate our methodologies. So far the only publicly available dataset of this nature is LL DARPA IDS evaluation dataset. The conclusions one can draw from evaluating on a single dataset is limited and we need to run our tool on other datasets to understand the effectiveness and generality of the methods. Relevant publications of the research can be found at:http://people.cis.ksu.edu/~xou/publications.htmlPublications #3,#5,#9 describe this research.Prioritizing intrusion analysis using dempster-shafer theory. Loai Zomlot, Sathya Chandran Sundaramurthy, Kui Luo, Xinming Ou, and S. Raj Rajagopalan. To appear in 4TH ACM Workshop on Artificial Intelligence and Security (AISec), Chicago, USA, Oct. 2011.Practical IDS alert correlation in the face of dynamic threats. Sathya Chandran Sundaramurthy, Loai Zomlot, and Xinming Ou. In The 2011 International Conference on Security and Management (SAM'11), Las Vegas, USA, July 2011. An empirical approach to modeling uncertainty in intrusion analysis. Xinming Ou, S. Raj Rajagopalan, and Sakthiyuvaraja Sakthivelmurugan. Annual Computer Security Applications Conference (ACSAC), Honolulu, Hawaii, USA, Dec 2009.If additional information is needed, please do not hesitate to contact me.Thanks,-Simon
column14: SKAION

column8: I am doing Master's thesis in networking and wanted to work on network traffic related data sets.Our main aim is to design a traffic analysis toolbox using Matlab, which would help a novice in performing all statistical operations pertaining to network traffic data. I am collecting data from different universities/sources, in order to validate my codes in MATLAB.I require the network traffic datasets, in order to carry out the visualization and perform statistical analysis on data.This would help us understand various factors which helps in either increase/decrease in network related performance such as end to end latency, traffic flow analysis, thresholding( critical alarms), link utilization and short/long term traffic.Which would further help in may be utilizing the resources to an optimum/acceptable level, so that one could decide where the entire bandwidth is been used/how effectively one could use it, depending upon the results obtained.

column8: We are working on a multi-population change-point detection problem, and as a potential application, would like to examine a way to apply this problem to detection of anomalies (intrusions, attacks) in computer networks' traffic. Aided with new real-world data, we intend to see if change-point detection in multiple populations can indeed be used for the aforementioned purpose.

column8: The analysis of this project centers around response times to DoS and DDoS attacks and attempts to apply game theoretic models to limit the damage of any particular attack. The data will be analyzed to begin formulating a methodology for creating a detailed DoS response game model.

column8: Utilize existing DHS data sets in conjunction with message traffic and web sites to build an integrated set of predictive models that help to predict likely sources and targets of cyber attacks. The goal is to develop the capability to correlate extensive structured and unstructured data and analyze it to identify emerging threats and predict likely attack venues. The second part of our effort will be to geo-tag the system and threat data and display it in a collaborative geospatial common operating picture. The goals are to clearly and intuitively show vulnerabilities, facilitate analyst collaboration and visualize attack parameters.
column14: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

column8: Utilize existing DHS data sets in conjunction with message traffic and web sites to build an integrated set of predictive models that help to predict likely sources and targets of cyber attacks. The goal is to develop the capability to correlate extensive structured and unstructured data and analyze it to identify emerging threats and predict likely attack venues. The second part of our effort will be to geo-tag the system and threat data and display it in a collaborative geospatial common operating picture. The goals are to clearly and intuitively show vulnerabilities, facilitate analyst collaboration and visualize attack parameters.

column6: Daniel Best - PNNL - PO Box 999 Richland WA 99354 - 509-372-6728 - daniel.best@pnnl.gov, Bryan Olsen - PNNL - PO Box 999 Richland WA 99354 - 509-372-6268 - bryan.olsen@pnnl.gov
column8: Our project seeks to develop behavioral modeling capabilities for hosts and/or gateways, based on analysis of connection-level variables contained in netflows or pcap headers.  We also develop large-scale visualization capabilities that support event detection and behavioral summarization in massive, streaming network traffic.  We are performing this work for DHS and other U.S. government agencies.  We seek long-term datasets on which to build models of characteristic activity for hosts and/or gateways, and to use for evaluation purposes.  When such datasets contain examples of known malicious activity, we validate that our modeling and visualization approaches can discover these events quickly.  We also verify that precursor events can be detected and flagged for a user of our tools.  The requested data sets will serve as additional testing input for our modeling approach.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column6: VANDANA JANEJA, UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND, BALTIMORE COUNTY1000 HILLTOP CIRCLE, BALTIMORE,MD 21250, (410)4556238, vjaneja@umbc.edu,RONALD TSAO, UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND, BALTIMORE COUNTY1000 HILLTOP CIRCLE, BALTIMORE,MD 21250, (410)4553249, ronaldt@umbc.edu
column8: For purposes of our research, we propose to use this data to study abnormalities in network activity.  An abnormality in network activity/traffic flow is determined by an unusual shift or increase from the base probability between two given nodes. The objective of this study is to understand and define the normal occurrence of activity on a network using a scanning approach, in order to be able to detect any anomalies or groups of anomalies (an anomalous window) in the traffic flow and how it related to particular topology of nodes in the network. The contributions of this study are directed towards providing new insights on the issue of cyber security, particularly from a data mining perspective.
column14: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

column8: In response to a recent "request for proposals" from the Institute for Homeland Security Solutions, I am interested in data to examine internet use over both space and time, specifically with the intent to understand how internet use has grown across countries and over time, and how the number of security threats (internet attacks or disruptions of various forms) have grown, too. With this data, I intend to use Econometric techniques to explain two features of internet use (the field of Econometrics is a specialty in Economics, where the econometrician applies advanced statistics to economic problems).  One, I can describe and explain the time series properties of internet use and disruptions to that use.  Understanding the time series properties of the data is fundamental to understanding how the phenomenon evolves and further understanding what might affect or disrupt internet traffic.  An analogy from economics in general would be Gross Domestic Product in the United States.  Econometricians take great pains to explain the time series properties of gross domestic product in order to understand how the long run trend changes over time and how the economy fluctuates around that trend.  My project is based on the premise that understanding how internet use evolves over time is important to explaining how policy makers may or may not be able to predict when a disruption will occur, just as economists attempt to predict when a recession might occur in the economy at large. The second feature of internet use that PREDICT data may allow me to explore is the cross-country characteristics of internet use (note, data collected both over space and time is known as Ã¢Â€Âœpanel dataÃ¢Â€Â to econometricians, or Ã¢Â€Âœlongitudinal dataÃ¢Â€Â in the social sciences more broadly).  Understanding how internet use has spread across countries over time may also be important for understanding the policy implications of internet attacks or disruptions.  The policy implications may include not just diplomatic conflict, but also measuring the cost of the disruptions emanating from one country on another countyÃ¢Â€Â™s economy, or the cost of guarding against future attacks or disruptions.  For the cyber world, an analogy from the real world is economists are interested in understanding how goods and services flow between countries, and then understanding the policy implications of the disruptions to that flow, such as arising from trade embargo or even from piracy. I am interested in the PREDICT data sets to see if they can be used in such a study as I have described.  Thus far, little has been said about the time series and longitudinal properties of internet traffic, no doubt due to the lack of data on the subject.  However, with the PREDICT data, I may be able to begin to piece together a panel data set in order to address the issues alluded to above.  I am interested in this data as an econometrician, but also, my employer, the US Naval Academy, has just begun an initiative to study Cyber Defense (and Warfare).  My current research project is motivated in part by that larger agenda.I am interested in this data as an econometrician, but also, my employer, the US Naval Academy, has just begun an initiative to study Cyber Defense (and Warfare).My current research project is motivated in part by that larger agenda.
column14: UCSD - Center for Applied Internet Data Analysis

column8: Network traffic modeling and anonymization research. Seeking packet data from diverse sources. Per Email 3-24/2011: The Columbia University Intrusion Detection Systems Lab is engaging in research in network data anonymization. We aim to develop machine learning algorithms which match hosts to groups of other hosts based on statistical profiles for their "behavior." By intermixing traffic from groups of similarly-behaving hosts, and assigning group identities, we aim to develop novel anonymization methodologies that provide anonymity to individual hosts within groups. Towards this end we are collecting packet-capture and netflow datasets from a variety of sources. We are looking for datasets that contain network traffic for a large amount of hosts, with long durations. We aim to extract behavior profiles from these hosts and evaluate our algorithms by splitting the dataset into train/test subsets, aiming to match the testing sub-flows with the training flows. We are not targeting USC data specifically, however, the description of the LANDERS dataset seem to match our desired properties in the data.Network traffic modeling and anonymization research. Seeking packet data from diverse sources.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: Our research is focused using bioinformatics techniques for analysis of netflow data.We have developed our techniques using internally collected netflow data, and now would like to access larger datasets for validation and verification of our algorithms.Specifically, our research focuses on three types of events:1) Outlier detection in very noisy datasets2) Detection of protocol/application masking, i.e., using a protocol to mask a different protocol and/or application. For example, running IP over DNS is a good example.3) Detection of a well known application running over unstandard port without doing deep packet inspection.
column14: Merit Network, Inc.

column6: Chris Oehmen, PNNL, 902 Battelle Blvd, Richland, WA,509/375-2038, christopher.oehmen@pnl.gov,Don Daly, PNNL, 902 Battelle Blvd, Richland, WA, 509/375-4365,don.daly@pnl.gov,Brett Matzke, PNNL, 902 Battelle Blvd, Richland, WA, 509/372-6162, brett.matzke@pnl.gov
column8: Our research is focused using bioinformatics techniques for analysis of netflow data.We have developed our techniques using internally collected netflow data, and now would like to access larger datasets for validation and verification of our algorithms.Specifically, our research focuses on three types of events:1) Outlier detection in very noisy datasets2) Detection of protocol/application masking, i.e., using a protocol to mask a different protocol and/or application. For example, running IP over DNS is a good example.3) Detection of a well known application running over unstandard port without doing deep packet inspection.
column14: Merit Network, Inc.

column6: Todd DeshaneClarkson University8 Clarkson Ave.BOX 581113699deshantm@gmail.com
column8: We are currently working with the Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL) on Mission Assurance Through Defensive Characterization (MADC).  Given a cyber network that supports some mission model,  we want to determine how occurrences in cyber space affect capabilities in mission space.   Specifically, given that some attack is happening on our network, we are interested in determining adversarial intent from information that we can gather on the network (i.e. traffic flows, IDS outputs) using pattern matching techniques with graphs of potential attacks. Although the specific details of IDS outputs are highly dependent upon the particular network and mission setting, our hope is to use the PREDICT datasets to begin to characterize the types of conclusions that can be drawn by data mining on the summary information as reported by IDS systems.

column8: Under contract DHS D10PC20039 associated with solicitation topic DHS SBIR H-SB010.2-003, we are developing the first level agents for a self organizating resilient network. This system is based on biological immune system and a new massively parallel pattern recognition technology. We are requesting access to these databases as a source of reliable data comprising normal and attack data. As a first step we are using IP Packet Header information to identify potential pakcets requiringj further attention. To accomplish this we need a variety of datasets where IP Header information is preserved and overall data stream includes both normal and attack data.  Access to this data provides us with uniform data to allow for testing and baselining activities
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column6: Joel Hypolite is the Principal Investigator. Others on this project are:1. Steven Gianvecchio, MITRE, 7515 Colshire Dr, McLean, VA 20175, 703-983-4115, gianvecchio@mitre.org2. Paul Seymer, MITRE, 7515 Colshire Dr, McLean, VA 20175, 703-983-2868, pseymer@mitre.org
column8: The purpose of the research project is to enhance our understanding of the adversary and malicious code by analyzing malicious datasets (including malware and network traffic containing malicious activity). This will enable us to then build network-based detection capabilities. We also seek benign datasets to train our anomaly detectors.

column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column6: Joe Head, Intrusion Inc, 1101 E Arapaho Rd Ste 200 Richardson Tx 75069, 972-301-3636, head@intrusion.com
column8: Intrusion Inc has made a survey of registered domain names and netblocks beginning ten years ago and continuing to the present.  I propose using the Internet Address Survey data to correlate with and validate the DNS and netblock data we have collect.  In addition I propose augmenting the Internet Address Survey with the DNS and netblock data.  The combined data would enable us to construct long term trending analysis and graphs.  I hope to answer the following questions Number of registered domain names that resolve to active hosts. Number of registered domain names that resolve to inactive hosts. Average Min and Max time between registration of a domain name and activation of of resolved address. Percent utilization of IP addresses in a given netblock, over time. Ratio of registered domain names verses active IP addresses in a given netblock.
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: I submitted a paper to the journal "Computer Communications" entitled "Improved Anomaly Detection Using Block-matching Denoising" describing a method for defeating DoS attacks. The reviews were generally good, but the DARPA dataset we used was referred to as obsolete. We would like a better dataset. From published papers, the datasets requested seem to satisfy this requirement.

column6: Rick Dove Paradigm Shift International2051 LAMA MOUNTAINPO BOX 289QUESTA, NM 87556-0289(575) 586-1536
column8: Under DHS SBIR H-SB010.2-003, we are developing the Sensing portion of a Self Organizing Resilient Network (SORN-S) by integrating existing natural-system process knowledge with a new affordable, massively-parallel, pattern-detection technology. The biological immune system (BIS) has been offered as a model by many who see its natural fit to cyber networks viewed as organisms, but computational performance limitations have obstructed necessary high fidelity translation. The cortical feed-forward/backward hierarchy is understood as a powerful pattern learner/predictor process, but computational translations remain complex and expensive. Both are compatible multi-agent architectural models that can be combined and distributed among existing network endpoints, potentially embedded in new systems designs, or packaged as a USB device for legacy add-on. A high fidelity BIS model adapted to cyber-networks offers both signature and behavior based detection of packet-born attacks and endpoint i
column14: University of Southern California-Information Sciences Institute

column8: We want to use the unsampled NetFlow data from the Merit routers for our TCP flow analysis, in which we aim to evaluate and estimate the total throughput of TCP flows in the current Internet at any given period. We will identify TCP flows in the datasets by the srcaddr, dstaddr, srcport, dstport, prot tuples in the packet headers. For each TCP flow, we will identify the time for its start and termination by looking for the SYN and FIN flags in the packets. We will then try to classify the various TCP flows into Atomic-service flows and Pipe-service flows, where the former represents the one-off communication pattern, while the latter represents long-lasting and bursty communication pattern. We will then evaluate that for each type of TCP flows, what is their total throughput at any given time. The results will be further used to evaluate our proposal of a new error-control mechanism for a clean-slate next-generation network design.
